title: yukio_(marvel)
body:
Yukio (雪緒) is a superhero appearing in American comic books published by [[marvel|Marvel Comics]]. She is a female ninja of Japanese origin and a supporting character of the [[X-Men]], particularly associated with [[wolverine (x-men)|Wolverine]].

Yukio appears in [[The Wolverine]] (2013), portrayed by Rila Fukushima. This version is a mutant with the ability to foresee others' deaths and was adopted by the Yashida family as a child to serve as a companion to Mariko Yashida. In the present, Yukio assists Logan in rescuing Mariko from Viper and Ichirō Yashida.

Yukio appears in [[Deadpool 2]], portrayed by Shioli Kutsuna. This version is a member of the X-Men and the girlfriend of teammate [[Negasonic Teenage Warhead]] with technical prowess and electrokinesis. Due to the latter power, fans suggested that the screenwriters had given Yukio's name to a different character, Surge, but the screenwriters denied this, insisting that Yukio remained the same character.

title: perfect_zeong
body:
A fictional manned giant robot from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse. It is a [[Mobile Suit]] in the [[Gundam MSV]] series.

The [[Zeong]] in the original [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] was an incomplete prototype; [[Char Aznable]] took to a [[space]] battle despite lacking its legs.

The [b]Perfect Zeong[/b] is what the Zeong would have been with extra armament and a pair of legs to aid balance and kick puny enemy mobile suits around with.
other_names: パーフェクト・ジオング

title: kitty_pryde
body: Katherine Anne "Kitty" Pryde is a character appearing in American comic books published by [[marvel|Marvel Comics]], commonly in association with the [[X-Men]]. The character first appeared in The Uncanny X-Men #129 (January 1980) and was co-created by writer-artist John Byrne and writer Chris Claremont. A mutant, Pryde possesses a "phasing" ability that allows her to pass through objects, hence she is intangible while using this ability. This power also disrupts any electrical field she passes through, and lets her simulate levitation.

title: independence_(azur_lane)
body:
[[Azur Lane]]'s personification of the US Navy light aircraft carrier USS [i]Independence[/i] (CVL-22). 
Character design by [[Atdan]], voiced by [[Yamazaki Haruka]].

h4. Appearance
In-game, she is depicted with [[long hair|long]] [[brown hair]] tied in a [[low ponytail]], with [[red eyes]]. She wears a sleeveless [[grey jacket]], [[black skirt]], [[blue coat]], [[red gloves]], tricolor (mostly blue) [[thighhighs]], and red [[rudder footwear]].
She is also shown holding a large [[bow (weapon)|]] and a [[quiver]], with her real-life bridge, crane, and spliced flight deck integral with the bow.

h4. History
In real life, she was originally built as the [[Cleveland (Azur Lane)|]]-class light cruiser USS [i]Amsterdam[/i] (CL-59), she was ordered converted into a light carrier in the first half of 1942 amid the urgency for carriers in the aftermath of Pearl Harbor. Commissioned in early January 1943, her first combat stint was a large airstrike on Rabaul in November aided by [[Saratoga (Azur Lane)|]], [[Essex (Azur Lane)|]], [[Bunker Hill (Azur Lane)|]], and her own sister ship [[Princeton (Azur Lane)|]].

Seeing service in Leyte Gulf and Okinawa, she was decommissioned in mid-1946 after being subjected to nuclear tests in [[Operation Crossroads]] alongside Saratoga. Highly radioactive, she was finally scuttled in 1951 off California.

title: montpelier_(azur_lane)
body:
The personification of the light cruiser USS [i]Montpelier[/i] (CL-57) in [[Azur Lane]]. Character design by [[Huanxiang Heitu]], voiced by [[Takahashi Rie]].

In-game, she has [[very long hair|very long]] silvery-[[grey hair]] with [[hair flaps|flaps]], and [[red eyes]]. She also wears a [[white cape]] like her sisters [[Cleveland (Azur Lane)|]] and [[Birmingham (Azur Lane)|]], a [[black shirt]] partially hidden by the cape and a red [[armband]] on the left sleeve, and black [[thighhighs]] with her name printed on it.

Her rig is the standard [i]Cleveland[/i]-class battle rig, with two 15.2 cm triple mounts on one side and two 12.7 twin mounts on the other, with two 20 mm Oerlikon AA guns on the side below the 15.2 cm mounts.

h4. Skins

* !post #3060296: Default
* !post #3364910: [[montpelier (flower of the snowy night) (azur lane)|Flower of the Snowy Night]]
* !post #4561348: [[montpelier (persephone's throne) (azur lane)|Persephone's Throne]]

h4. History
She is often depicted with three particular sister ships: Cleveland, Columbia, and Denver. They are called in-game as the "Solomon Knights" and were known as Cruiser Division 12 (CruDiv12) in real life. Montpelier is also SR (SSR in the JP and CN servers) rarity, the first in the class, as she was historically the CruDiv's flagship.

body:
The personification of the US Navy light cruiser USS [i]Columbia[/i] (CL-56) in [[Azur Lane]]. Character design by [[Hao (patinnko)|]], voiced by Horigome Saya.

In-game, she is portrayed having [[long hair|long]] [[blonde hair]] and [[red eyes]], with [[sunglasses]] on her head. She is wearing a blue-white shirt with a [[star print]], [[dog tags]], [[blue shorts]], [[brown belt]], and a striped [[single thighhigh]] on her left leg.

Her rig is the same as her sisters, with two 15.2 cm triple mounts on one side and two 12.7 cm twin mounts on another. Unlike [[Montpelier (Azur Lane)|]], she does not have 20 mm Oerlikon AA guns on her rig.

She is also shown [[chewing gum|chewing on bubble gum]] in her base art.

h4. History
In real life, Columbia was among the first of her class to enter service alongside Cleveland, Montpelier, and Denver (the so-called "Solomon Knights"/Cruiser Division 12). Together they saw service at the battles of Rennell Island and Empress Augusta Bay.
She later joined Denver in the battle of Leyte Gulf, facing off against "Nishimura's fleet.":/pools/9549

After seeing further service in Lingayen Gulf and Borneo, she was decommissioned in 1946.

title: lobo_(dc)
body: Lobo (Iberian for "wolf") is a fictional character appearing in comic books published by [[DC Comics]]. He was created by Roger Slifer and Keith Giffen, and first appeared in Omega Men #3 (June 1983). He is an [[alien]] from the utopian planet of Czarnia, and works as an interstellar mercenary and bounty hunter.

title: sinestro
body: Thaal Sinestro (/sɪˈnɛstroʊ/) (or simply Sinestro) is a supervillain appearing in American comic books published by [[DC Comics]], particularly those featuring [[Green Lantern]]. Created by John Broome and Gil Kane, Sinestro is a former Green Lantern Corps member who was dishonorably discharged for abusing his power. He has since endured as the archenemy of the superhero Green Lantern and is the founder of the Sinestro Corps.

title: the_question
body: The Question is a name used by several fictional characters appearing in American comic books published by [[DC Comics]]. Created by Steve Ditko, the Question first appeared in Charlton Comics' [[Blue Beetle]] #1 (June 1967), and was acquired by DC Comics in the early 1980s and incorporated into the DC Universe.

title: black_canary
body: Black Canary is the name of two superheroines appearing in American comic books published by [[DC Comics]]. As one of the earliest female superheroes in the DC Comics universe, the character has made numerous appearances in prominent team-up titles, including the Justice Society of America and [[Justice League]] of America. The Black Canary persona has been adopted by two individuals, portrayed as a legacy heroes with a mother-daughter relationship between the two. Following DC's New 52 initiative, Black Canary was briefly amalgamated as a single character before the mother-and-daughter dynamic was restored to continuity, the history formerly established retroactively added as part of the second Black Canary's history.

title: martian_manhunter
body: The Martian Manhunter (J'onn J'onzz) is a superhero in American comic books published by [[DC Comics]]. Created by writer Joseph Samachson and artist Joe Certa, the character first appeared in the story "The Manhunter from Mars" in Detective Comics #225 (November 1955). Martian Manhunter is one of the seven original members of the [[Justice League]] of America and one of the most powerful beings in the DC Universe.

title: sonic_generations
body:
[b]Sonic Generations[/b] (ソニック ジェネレーションズ [i]Sonikku Jenerēshonzu[/i]) is a 2011 platformer video game developed by [[Sonic Team]] and published by [[Sega]] for the Xbox 360, PlayStation 3, PC, and Nintendo 3DS.

Produced in commemoration of the 20th anniversary of the Sonic the Hedgehog series, the game follows [[Sonic the Hedgehog|Sonic]] and [[Tails (Sonic)|]] as they form an alliance with their past selves to stop an evil entity from erasing all time. It features two gameplay styles: "Classic", which plays from a side-scrolling perspective like that of the original [[Sega Mega Drive]] [[Sonic the Hedgehog (classic)|Sonic games]], and "Modern", 3D levels similar to those in [[Sonic Unleashed]] and [[Sonic Colors]].

The Japanese version has different subtitles, [b]White Time and Space[/b] (白の時空 [i]Shiro no Jikū[/i]) for the home consoles, and [b]Blue Adventures[/b] (青の冒険 [i]Ao no Bōken[/i]) for the 3DS version.

A remastered version, [[Sonic x Shadow Generations]], was released in 2024.

h4. External links
* "Sonic Retro: Sonic Generations":https://info.sonicretro.org/Sonic_Generations
* "Wikipedia: Sonic Generations":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sonic_Generations
other_names: ソニックジェネレーションズ

title: sonic_x_shadow_generations
body: A remaster and companion game release of the console/PC version of [[Sonic Generations]] developed by Sonic Team, featuring additional new content with [[Shadow the Hedgehog]] as a playable character. The re-release version contains a new campaign called "Shadow Generations", centering on Shadow as he must stop [[Black Doom]] from taking over the world, as well as new features to Sonic Generations.

title: lazytown
body:
[b]Latibær[/b] (EN: [b]LazyTown[/b]) is a children's educational musical comedy TV series from Iceland. It aired from 2004 to 2014.

The series focuses on eight-year-old Stephanie (Julianna Rose Mauriello in seasons 1-2, Chloe Lang in seasons 3-4) who has just moved to LazyTown. With the help of a “slightly above average” superhero named [[Sportacus]] (Magnus Scheving), she helps the residents of the town live more active lifestyles.

The show became a meme in 2016 with the song We Are Number One, sang by the villain [[Robbie Rotten]] (Stefán Karl Stefánsson), who at the time had cancer.

title: partido_verde_ecologista_de_mexico
body: The Ecologist Green Party of Mexico (Spanish: Partido Verde Ecologista de México, pronounced [paɾˈtiðo ˈβeɾðe ekoloˈxista ðe ˈmexiko], PVEM or PVE) is a green political party in [[Mexico]]. Founded in 1986, the party is associated with Jorge González Torres and his son Jorge Emilio González Martínez. It has seldom gotten more than 10% of the vote nationwide, but in the 21st century has joined alliances with different major parties (PAN in the federal elections of 2000, PRI from 2003 to 2018, and most recently MORENA from 2019 on).

title: aoraki_(racehorse)
body:
[tn]Named after the Māori name of Mount Cook.[/tn]

Real-Life Japanese Thoroughbred racehorse. Sired by [[Gold Ship (racehorse)|]] and foaled by (New Zealand-bred white horse) Casta Diva. A third-generation descendant of The Opera House's lineage of white horses, he is himself a white horse with blue eyes and a wild disposition that is a perfect match for "Horse Whisperer" jockey [[Ikezoe Ken'ichi]].

He is actually the first of three white horses sired by Gold Ship, the two others being Satono Jasmine's [[Gorgeous (JPN) (2022) (racehorse)|2022]] and 2023 foals (Satono Jasmine being from the White Beauty lineage), both fillies.

After being winless in 17 races in Central, he was sent to the regionals in Nagoya, where, in his second try at Kasamatsu, he finally won his first race.

title: hachimaki
body:
A type of Japanese [[headband]] made of cloth or twine worn to signify dedication to extreme effort. 
A plane hachimaki is commonly used in a sports day / festival of Japanese school to indicate the team color and to try to increase their motivations / kiai (気合, "fighting spirit").
Another common type of hachimaki is printed a red circle of Japanese flag or previously rising sun emblem or / and a short inspirational slogan meant to be displayed across the forehead.

If the headband is twisted, that is called a [[nejiri hachimaki]] which is commonly worn by participants of a Japanese festival.

h4. Examples
* !post #7846176: Red and white hachimakis are worn  in the sports day at school.
* !post #5612240: A red hachimaki with a [[gakuran]].
* !post #7552466: Wearing a white hachimaki with a red circle and a short slogan as a part of an [[ouendan]] uniform.
* !post #7604955: Wearing a hachimaki in order to boost her motivation.
* !post #7585504: Wearing a hachimaki with a message to the [[idol]] her cheering.
* !post #7937430: [[nejiri hachimaki]]  [tn]| A traditional hachimaki worn during festivals (often with a [[mizu happi]]).[/tn]

title: disneyland
body:
Disneyland is the name applied to any of several of [[Disney]]'s [[amusement_park|theme parks]] around the world, including the original in California.

[b]Tokyo Disneyland[/b] (東京ディズニーランド, Tōkyō Dizunīrando) is a 115 acre (465,000 m²) theme park at the Tokyo Disney Resort located in Urayasu, Chiba, Japan, near Tokyo. The park was constructed by Walt Disney Imagineering in the same style as Disneyland in California and Magic Kingdom in Florida. Also at Tokyo Disney Resort is [[Tokyo DisneySea]] (東京ディズニーシー, Tōkyō DizunīShī) and Ikspiari (イクスピアリ), the domestic equivalents of DisneySea and Downtown Disney.

There are seven themed areas in the park: the World Bazaar; the four classic Disney lands: Adventureland, Westernland, Fantasyland and Tomorrowland; and two mini-lands: Critter Country and Mickey's Toontown. The park is noted for its extensive open spaces, to accommodate the large crowds that visit the park. In 2009, Tokyo Disneyland hosted approximately 13.65 million guests, ranking it as the third-most visited theme park in the world, behind its American sister parks, Magic Kingdom and Disneyland.

title: the_haunted_mansion
body:
A long-running attraction in [[disneyland|Walt Disney Theme Parks]]. The mansion, as its title implies, is inhabited by ghosts, and  the audience does a tour of the house. Its best known feature is the Stretching Room, a small room in the mansion with four large portraits that "stretches"  to reveal the more macabre halves of the portraits hanging above the audience; and the Ballroom, with illusions of dozens of ghosts waltzing.

A movie based on the attraction was released in 2003. Another one released in 2023, unrelated to the 2003 movie. Its Hong Kong Disneyland equivalent is the Mystic Manor.

title: nurse
body:
When a character is wearing the attire of a nurse. A nurse is a health care professional who regularly assists [[doctor|doctors]] and other health care professionals in the [[syringe|treatment]], safety, and recovery of [[sick|ill]] and [[injury|injured people]]. Nursing is largely a female profession, but men can be nurses as well.

While most modern nurses wear [[medical scrubs]] at their workplaces, the attire this tag most often applies to is the [[white dress]] and [[nurse cap]] combination that was popular during the 20th century. Before then, western nurses were known for wearing a combination of a nurse cap, [[black dress]], and a [[white apron]].

title: grogu
body:
A fictional [[alien]] character from the [[Star Wars]] universe.

[spoilers]An infant (roughly 50 years old during the events of [[The Mandalorian]]) member of [[Yoda]]'s species, found by [[Din Djarin]] who then starts to watch over him. A former member of the [[Jedi]] Order, he was saved by another Jedi during [[star_wars:_revenge_of_the_sith|order 66 and the clone trooper attack on the Jedi Temple]].[/spoilers] 

Because his real name wasn't known until chapter 13 of [i]The Mandalorian[/i], other characters mostly referred to him as just [b]the Child[/b] for the first 12 chapters; however, he was arguably better known among viewers by the nickname [b]Baby Yoda[/b].

title: gundam_unicorn
body:
7 episode [[Gundam]] OVA series running from 2010-14, adapted from the 10 volume novel series by Harutoshi Fukui. Occurs in [b]Universal Century 0096[/b], three years after [[Char's Counterattack]].

The series revolves around the pursuit of Laplace's Box, a MacGuffin said to contain a secret that could bring down the [[Earth Federation]] government, by [[Neo Zeon]] remnants calling themselves "The Sleeves" and Londo Bell, the [[earth_federation_space_forces|EFSF]] special taskforce from Char's Counterattack. The titular [[Unicorn Gundam]] acts as both a map and key to the Box, coordinates to which are encrypted in its operating system.

Chronologically continued by [[Gundam Narrative]].

h4.Related characters:

* [[Banagher Links]], pilot of the Unicorn Gundam

title: blex_forer
body:
A fictional character from the [[Gundam]] universe. He first appeared in the [[Zeta Gundam]] anime TV series from 1985.

[b]Blex Forer[/b] is the [[military]] veteran leader of the [[aeug|Anti Earth Union Group]] (or more correctly translated, the Anti United Earth Government Group), who travels aboard the [[Argama]] during its initial tour of duty. 
 
A [[serious]], intelligent and calm looking, [[beard]]ed [[blonde hair]]ed man. Formerly a high-ranking officer in the [[Earth Federation Space Forces]], Blex was outraged by the atrocities of [[titans_(gundam)|the Titans]], and used his political and business connections with [[Anaheim Electronics]] to organize a very well armed, well supplied and well equipped resistance group. 

Well-acquainted with his enemies [[Bask Om]] and [[Jamitov Hymen]], Blex plots his counter-strategies against them with the calm intelligence of a veteran [[chess]] player. [spoilers]However, he is betrayed and shot by a Titans operative during a peace summit in the city of Dakar and dies in the arms of [[Quattro Bajeena]], telling him to become the new leader of the AEUG, but as [[Char Aznable]], the legendary "Red Comet" from [[Zeon]].[/spoilers]

title: dr._evil
body: Douglas "Dougie" Powers, commonly known as Dr. Evil, is a fictional character portrayed by Mike Myers in the [[Austin Powers]] film series. He is the main antagonist and Austin Powers' nemesis (and secret twin brother). He is a parody of [[James Bond]] villains, primarily Ernst Stavro Blofeld. Dr. Evil routinely hatches schemes to terrorize and take over the world, and is usually accompanied by "Number Two", his second-in-command who fronts his evil corporation Virtucon Industries, his personal assistant Frau Farbissina, and his sidekick Mini-Me, a dwarf clone of himself.

title: chris_griffin
body:
One of the main characters in [[Family Guy]].

He is the middle child of the Griffin family. He is 13 in the first three seasons, 14 in the fourth through nineteenth season, and 15 in the twentieth season. Son of [[Peter Griffin|Peter]] and [[Lois Griffin]].
He is voiced by the American actor, producer, and writer [[Seth Green]] and first appeared on television, along with the rest of the Griffin family, in the episode "Death Has a Shadow" on January 31, 1999.

title: seth_green
body:
Seth Benjamin Green (né Gesshel-Green; born February 8, 1974) is an American actor. His film debut came with a role in the comedy-drama film The Hotel New Hampshire (1984), and he went on to have supporting roles in comedy films throughout the 1980s, including Radio Days (1987) and Big Business (1988).
During the 1990s and 2000s, Green began starring in comedy films such as Idle Hands (1999), Rat Race (2001), Without a Paddle (2004) and Be Cool (2005). He also became known for his portrayal of Scott Evil, Dr. Evil's son, in the [[Austin Powers]] film series (1997–2002). Green has also taken serious roles in films, including The Attic Expeditions (2001) and Party Monster (2003). He has provided the voice for Howard the Duck in a number of [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] films and series, including [[Guardians of the Galaxy]] (2014), [[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 2]] (2017), and [[Guardians of the Galaxy Vol. 3]] (2023) and in the animated series What If...? (2021–present). In 2019, he wrote, directed, and starred in the comedy-drama film Changeland.
Green's first lead role on television was on the ABC sitcom Good & Evil in 1991, for which he won a Young Artist Award. Green later gained attention for his supporting roles as Oz, a teenage guitarist and the boyfriend of Willow Rosenberg, on the fantasy television series [[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]] (1997–2000), and as the voice of [[Chris Griffin]] on the Fox adult animated comedy series [[Family Guy]] (1999–present). He also voiced Leonardo in the Nickelodeon animated series [[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]] (2014–2017) and Joker in the Mass Effect video game series (2007–2012). Green created, directed, wrote, and produced the adult animated comedy series [[Robot Chicken]] and its spinoffs (2005–present), which have earned him three Primetime Emmy Awards and five Annie Awards.

title: tie_fighter_(video_game)
body: Star Wars: TIE Fighter is a 1994 [[Star Wars]] space flight simulator and space combat video game, a sequel in the Star Wars: X-Wing series. It places the player in the role of an Imperial starfighter pilot during events that occur between [[Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back|The Empire Strikes Back]] and [[star wars: Return of the Jedi|Return of the Jedi]]

title: ithorian
body: Ithorians, commonly referred to as hammerheads or as leathernecks as an insult, were a sentient species from the planet Ithor in the [[Star Wars]] franchise. Ithorians had two mouths on the opposite sides of their necks, giving them a deep, rumbling voice. Most Ithorians were peaceful and revered nature. The species' pacifism was so strong that they exiled violent individuals from their homeworld of Ithor. Notable Ithorians include Dok-Ondar, a collector on Batuu, and Momaw Nadon, an Ithorian gardener who was exiled from his homeworld.

[spoiler]Because of her Aegirian race, her family was persecuted by the Inquisition and the townsfolk of their village. She was rescued by a bishop of the Church of the Deep, who promised her an idealistic world if she let him transform her into a Seaborn. Realizing that she wouldn't be able to sing anymore, she rejects her new form mid-transformation and is rescued by [[Mizuki (arknights)|]], who brings her to Rhodes Island.[/spoiler]

Her motif is based on Violescent sea-whip corals.

Her [[voice actor]]s are Ooshita Natsumi (Japanese), Xu Xiaowen (Chinese), Ashlyn Madden (English), and Lee Da-eun (Korean). Her art designer is [[hoirn|Horin_]].

title: itchy_&_scratchy
body: The Itchy & Scratchy Show (often shortened as Itchy & Scratchy) is a fictional animated series featured on [[The Simpsons]]. The cartoon depicts a sadistic mouse named Itchy whom repeatedly maims or murders a black cat named Scratchy. It is typically presented as 15- to 60-second sketches that are a part of The [[Krusty the Clown]] Show. Itchy & Scratchy is filled with graphic violence, unsuitable for children, that almost invariably prompts laughter from The Simpsons characters, especially [[bart simpson|Bart]] and [[lisa simpson|Lisa]].

title: optimus_prime
body:
One of the most recognizable [[Transformers]] that first appeared in the original [[Transformers: Generation 1]] TV cartoon from 1984. The heroic, wise and powerful Optimus Prime leads the [[Autobot]]s against [[Megatron]], the evil leader of the [[Decepticon]]s.

In the first series his alternate mode is a red, silver and blue Kenworth K100 cab over [[truck]]. But since his [[transformers (live action)|appearance in the the live action movie]], he is also frequently depicted as a red and blue [[Peterbilt 379]] [[semi truck]] with distinctive flame paintjob.

Before becoming leader of the Autobots, Optimus [spoiler]used to be a smaller robot called [[Orion Pax]]. He was mortally damaged by Megatron, but Alpha Trion reconstructed him into the ultimate powerful form of Optimus Prime.[/spoiler]

In [[Japan]] (except for the Japanese dubs of the live-action films and of [[Transformers Animated]]), Optimus Prime is known as [b]Convoy[/b].
 
His quote in the G1 series, "”I've got an idea.”":[http://dic.pixiv.net/a/%E7%A7%81%E3%81%AB%E3%81%84%E3%81%84%E8%80%83%E3%81%88%E3%81%8C%E3%81%82%E3%82%8B] is regarded as a type of [[meme]] among Japanese Transformers fandom due to its low success rate.

Optimus Prime's original G1 design was created by [[mecha]] designers Obara Hiroyuki, [[Kawamori Shouji]] (famous for his work in [[Macross]]) and Ohno Kouhjin for the [[Diaclone]] Japanese transforming robot toy series in the early 1980s.

[quote]Motto: [i]"Freedom is the right of all sentient beings...".[/i][/quote]

h4. See also

* [[Omega Prime]]
* [[Elita One]]
* [[Orion Pax]]
* [[Convoy (armada)|]] 
* [[Optimus Prime (Transformers Prime)]]

title: leverless_arcade_stick
body:
A variant of an [[arcade stick]] where the traditional joystick is replaced by four buttons representing the four cardinal directions that would normally be controlled by the stick.

Popularized by the [[Hit Box (controller)|]] from the US, these sorts of controllers were developed to allow [[fighting game]] players who had primarily played online on PCs with [[computer keyboard]]s to use a controller with a similar form factor for offline events, where consoles are the preferred platform for organizational purposes. The ease with which leverless controllers allowed directional inputs to be hit, along with the improved ergonomics that an all-button design allowed for, saw the form factor explode in popularity throughout the 2010s and into the 2020s.

title: arcade_stick
body:
A type of [[game controller]] that is designed to be a portable version of an arcade cabinet's ball joystick and large buttons. It is designed to be a home version of a cabinet's setup, making arcade ports for consoles easier to play.

The Japanese term for it is "arcade controller" (アーケードコントローラー). In English it's also known as a "fightstick", since it's especially popular with fighting game enthusiasts.

title: chapman_stick_(instrument)
body:
The Chapman Stick is an electric musical instrument devised by Emmett Chapman in the early 1970s. A member of the guitar family, the Chapman Stick usually has ten or twelve individually tuned strings and is used to play bass lines, melody lines, chords, or textures. Designed as a fully polyphonic chordal instrument, it can also cover several of these musical parts simultaneously.

h4. See also:

title: godzilla_minus_one
body:
A 2023 [[Godzilla (series)|]] movie produced by Toho Films. It is set in the immediate aftermath of World War II and served as a soft reboot to the original 1954 movie.

Won an [[The Academy Awards|Oscar (Academy Award)]] for Best Visual Effects.

Features a scene involving the cruiser [i]Takao[/i] and Godzilla, leading to fan art involving Takao's [i][[Takao (Kancolle)|Kantai Collection]][/i] and [i][[Takao (Azur Lane)|Azur Lane]][/i] personifications. Another scene involving the destroyers [i][[Hibiki (Kancolle)|Hibiki]][/i] and [i][[Yukikaze (Kancolle)|Yukikaze]][/i] has likewise led to fan art featuring their Kantai Collection personifications.

title: azazel_(x-men)
body: Azazel is a character appearing in American comic books published by [[marvel|Marvel Comics]]. Created by Chuck Austen and Sean Philips, the character first appeared in Uncanny [[X-Men]] #428 (August 2003). He belongs to the subspecies of humans named mutants, who are born with superhuman abilities. He is the father of the X-Men's Kiwi Black and was originally the father of [[Nightcrawler]] as well until that was retconned in 2023.

title: witch_king_of_angmar
body: The Lord of the Nazgûl, also called the Witch-king of Angmar, the Pale King, or Black Captain, is a fictional character in J. R. R. Tolkien's fantasy novel [[The Lord of the Rings]]. He was one of the Nine among Men that the dark lord Sauron gave Rings of Power, becoming Nazgûl or Ringwraiths. His ring gives him great power, but enslaves him to Sauron and makes him invisible. As a wraith, he had once established himself King of Angmar in the north of Eriador. In the events of the Lord of the Rings, he stabs the bearer of the One Ring, the Hobbit [[Frodo Baggins]], with a Morgul-knife which would reduce its victim to a wraith. Much later, in his final battle, the Lord of the Nazgûl attacks Éowyn with a mace. The Hobbit Merry Brandybuck stabs him with an ancient enchanted Númenórean blade, allowing Éowyn to kill him with her sword.

title: eowyn
body: Éowyn is a fictional character in J. R. R. Tolkien's [[The Lord of the Rings]]. She is a noblewoman of Rohan who describes herself as a shieldmaiden.

title: gimli
body: Gimli is a fictional character in J. R. R. Tolkien's Middle-earth, appearing in [[The Lord of the Rings]]. A dwarf warrior, he is the son of Glóin, a member of Thorin's company in Tolkien's earlier book The Hobbit. He represents the race of Dwarves as a member of the Fellowship of the Ring. As such, he is one of the primary characters in the story. In the course of the adventure, Gimli aids the Ring-bearer [[Frodo Baggins]], participates in the War of the Ring, and becomes close friends with Legolas, overcoming an ancient enmity of Dwarves and Elves.

Bender doesn't seem to care for Tinny Tim and is very cruel to him, both directly and indirectly. In one case Tinny Tim saves Bender from getting arrested and helps him to join the Robot Mafia. He is friends with Dwight and Cubert.

body: Character from [[Futurama]], Captain Zapp Brannigan (born June 30, 2972) is an egotistical, jerkish and perverted military officer for the Democratic Order of Planets and Earth's Government and captain of at least a ship: usually of the Earth ship Nimbus, but briefly of the luxury liner Titanic. Later in the series, he is introduced as a Twenty-Five Star General or General Major Webelo.

title: john_a_zoidberg
body:
Dr. John A. Zoidberg, often referred to mononymously as Zoidberg, is a fictional character from the animated series [[Futurama]] and is the series' comic relief. He is a Decapodian, a crustacean-like species of [[alien]], who works as the staff doctor for Planet Express, despite his woeful understanding of human physiology and allusions to his questionable credentials.

Zoidberg is named after an Apple II game that series writer David X. Cohen created in high school called Zoid, similar to the game Qix. The game was rejected by Broderbund. One of Cohen's inspirations for the character of Dr. Zoidberg was the fact that [[Star Trek]] character [[Leonard McCoy]], the ship's doctor, frequently administered medical treatment to aliens such as [[Spock]], so Cohen wished human characters in Futurama to be in the uneasy situation of being treated by an alien doctor.

title: natasha_romanoff

Romanoff is depicted as an expert spy and hand-to-hand combatant, trained in the Red Room from childhood to be a KGB assassin. This brought her under S.H.I.E.L.D.'s radar, and Clint Barton was sent to kill her but instead spared her life and recruited her into the organization.

title: primrose_(flower)
body:
A common name for many [[flower]]s of the genus [b][i]Primula[/i][/b], family [i]Primulaceae[/i], native mostly to cool or mountainous regions of the Northern Hemisphere. Some of the commonly depicted species are [i]Primula vulgaris[/i] and its hybrid [i]Primula polyantha[/i], the common primrose, and [i]Primula sieboldii[/i], the Japanese or cherry blossom primrose.

Primrose flowers have five petals, usually with a notch in each petal. Depending on the species, the notch may be shallow or go deep into the petal. The tips are usually rounded. The flowers can be almost any color, and the petals usually change color toward the center, often to a bright yellow or orange. Depending on the species, the leaves may be ovate (egg-shaped), obovate (drop-shaped), or spatulate (spoon-shaped). Some species, such as the common primrose, have very distinctive wrinkled leaves that form a rosette. Many species are low-growing.

The genus is not closely related to [[rose]]s or to [[Oenothera (flower)|]] (commonly called evening primrose).

h4. Examples

title: ground_gm
body:
A fictional manned giant robot from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse. It first appeared in the [[Gundam 08th MS Team]] OVA series form 1996.

[b]RGM-79 [G] GM Ground Type[/b]

An early version of the [[Earth Federation]] [[gm_(mobile_suit)|GM]] [[mobile suit]] intended to fight in ground combat. It was somewhat clunky and underperforming compared to the standard GM, and was phased out as the production model rolled out, but it had tougher armor made of Luna Titanium around its vitals and could use a powerful [[beam rifle]]. 

Its combat performance was sturdy enough to warrant its continued use in a few units, in spite of a shortage of spare parts.

title: uncensored
body:
An image that has not been [[censored]] by the artist. See [[decensored]] for images that have been decensored by a [[third-party edit]].

This tag applies only to genitalia, sex acts, body fluids, or other things that would normally be censored. It does not apply to [[nipples]], or to body parts that aren't fully visible. Note that this tag is mutually exclusive from [[censored]], and that both tags can be applied if one of the chracter's genitalia is left uncensored.

In Japan, it is illegal to draw uncensored genitalia if they are to be published publicly for domestic distribution. Some artists skirt around this law by applying censorship that is easy to remove, or by applying [[pointless censoring|pointless censorship]] that barely hides the censored body part. Others maintain a non-Japanese presence to bypass Japanese laws altogether and distribute uncensored versions of their work. It is also noted that some censorship also doubles as a paywall or sample work of sorts, with the uncensored version available in an artists' donation page, such as Patreon, Fanbox and others.

h4. See also

* [[censored]]
* [[decensored]]
* [[Tag group:Censorship]]

title: stranger_things
body:
[b]Stranger Things[/b] is an American supernatural horror and [[science fiction]] web television series created by the Duffer Brothers. It is written and directed by Matt and Ross Duffer and executive produced by Shawn Levy. 

It stars Winona Ryder, David Harbour, Finn Wolfhard, Millie Bobby Brown, Gaten Matarazzo, Caleb McLaughlin, Natalia Dyer, Charlie Heaton, Cara Buono, and Matthew Modine. 

The show is set in 1983 in the fictional town of Hawkins, Indiana, and is an homage to 80s pop culture, inspired and aesthetically informed by the works of [[Steven Spielberg]], John Carpenter, Stephen King, and [[George Lucas]], among others.

The show was released on [[Netflix]] on July 15, 2016. It received critical acclaim for its characterization, pacing, atmosphere, acting, soundtrack, directing, writing, and homages to 1980s genre films. On August 31, 2016, Netflix renewed the series for a second season of nine episodes, released in 2017. It was followed by two more seasons in 2019 and 2022. The fifth and final season is expected to be released in 2025.

title: nyanko/wanko_to_mahou_no_boushi
body:
Literally "Kitty/Puppy and the Magic Hat".

A pair of adventure games for the Wii and Playstation 2 developed by Yuke's, released in 2007. It is the spiritual successor to [[The DOG Island: Hitotsu no Hana no Monogatari]]. The two versions of the game are identical in every way besides whether the cast consists of cats or dogs.

The plot centers around the protagonist being tricked by the antagonist, the wolf [[Ivlet]], into giving him a magic hat that keeps peace on the island they reside in.

Localized by [[Ubisoft]] as Petz: Catz 2 and Petz: Dogz 2, adopting it into an unrelated series they own the rights to and marketing it as a much more generic game.

title: bache_(azur_lane)
body:
[[Azur Lane]]'s personification of the American destroyer [i]Bache[/i].
Character design by [[waterkuma]], voiced by Kaneko Sayaka.

h4. Appearance and personality
Her design as well as her personality were based on a [[pun]] of her name that reads almost the same as the word "bitch". As such, she is depicted as a "[[mesugaki]]" [[gyaru]]. She has a [[very long hair|very long]] [[blonde hair]] with [[two side up]] and a [[purple eyes]], she wears a [[black_headwear|black]] [[sailor hat]] with golden anchor decoration, a golden [[fur trim]]med [[jacket]], a [[black_shirt|black]] [[sleeveless]] [[crop top]] [[serafuku]] with a yellow ribbon, a [[pink collar]] with a golden ring, and a [[short shorts|very short]] [[denim shorts]]. 

h4. Skins
* !post #3611916: Default
* !post #3639441: [[Bache (Gorgeous Speed-Star) (Azur Lane)|Gorgeous Speed-Star]]
* !post #3836610: [[Bache (Showy Sports Star) (Azur Lane)|Showy Sports Star]]

h4. History
The historical [i]Bache[/i] was launched in 7 July 1942. After being assigned to several bombardment mission in late 1943, she took part in the "Battle of Surigao Strait":/pools/9549 before sent back to the United States in late 1944 for her first overhaul. After completion, she was sent to cover fire support at [[Iwo Jima]] before being struck by a kamikaze attack on 13 May 1945, forcing her to return to the US and receive her second overhaul. After the war, she has been converted two times, first in 1950 as an escort destroyer, before being converted back into a destroyer in 1962.  On 6 Febuary 1968, [i]Bache[/i] was stuck by a gale during her visit on the Isle of Rhodes, Greece, and ran aground. Ironically for the in-game emphasis on her character, the US Navy deemed her unrecoverable and she was sold for scrap there.

title: atlanta_(azur_lane)
body:
The [[Azur Lane]] personification of the light cruiser USS [i]Atlanta[/i] (CL-51).

She was commissioned 24 December 1941 and was awarded 5 battle stars and a Presidential Unit Citation during [[World War II]]. After sinking the Japanese destroyer [[akatsuki (azur lane)|Akatsuki]], Atlanta was heavily damaged by Japanese and friendly gunfire (from [[San Francisco (Azur Lane)|]] as attested by the green dye splotches found on Atlanta's bridge a few hours later, which San Francisco used for her shells) in a night surface action on 13 November 1942 during the Naval Battle of Guadalcanal. The cruiser was sunk on her captain's orders in the afternoon of the same day.

Is depicted as being the elder sister-type to her sisters.

title: ariake_(azur_lane)
body:
[[Azur Lane]]'s personification of the Japanese destroyer [i]Ariake[/i], fifth of the [i]Hatsuharu[/i]-class.

h4. Appearance

h4. History
The historical [i]Ariake[/i] was the fifth of the [i]Hatsuharu[/i]-class but the first in an "improved design" that was meant to remedy the chronic stability issues of the first four [i]Hatsuharu[/i]s. Aside from lowered superstructures and a revised weapons suite, she and her sister ship [[Yuugure (Azur Lane)|]] were the first destroyers fitted with the 12.7 cm twin Type C mounts as used by the succeeding [[Shiratsuyu (Azur Lane)|]], [[Asashio (Azur Lane)|]], and [[Kagerou (Azur Lane)|]] classes. In addition, they both received two rudders, one aft of each propeller, in an attempt to reduce severe heeling at turns, only to have them removed after their trials in 1935 as the same design changes made the use of twin rudders redundant.

Assigned to DesDiv 27, they escorted the Second Carrier Division ([[Hiryuu (Azur Lane)|]] and [[Souryuu (Azur Lane)|]]) in raids on Rabaul and Darwin. They repeated the same task for the Fifth CarDiv ([[Shoukaku (Azur Lane)|]] and [[Zuikaku (Azur Lane)|]]) in the battle of the Coral Sea.

She was sunk on July 28, 1943 by engaging B-25 Mitchell bombers while assisting [[Mikazuki (Azur Lane)|]]. This was after completing a troop transport at Tuluvu, New Britain (now part of Papua New Guinea), during which the two destroyers ran aground on a reef off Cape Gloucester.

For her retrofit form, see her [[ariake (retrofit) (azur lane)|corresponding page.]]

title: odin_(azur_lane)
body:
The personification of the cancelled German battlecruiser [i]Odin[/i] as depicted in [[Azur Lane]]'s collaboration with [[World of Warships]].

Odin is introduced in [[World of Warships]] as a Design for the preceding Admiral Graf Spee, Deutschland Panzerschiff class and Scharnhorst class, armed with 3x3 305mm guns. Unlike most battleships, and much like Tirpitz, Odin carried torpedo armament in her planned design.

title: albacore_(azur_lane)
body:
[[Azur Lane]]'s personification of the US Navy submarine USS [i]Albacore[/i] (SS-218). Character design by [[Kani Biimu]], voiced by [[Tanezaki Atsumi]].

She has [[long hair|long]] [[blonde hair]] and [[aqua eyes]], and wears a [[black bikini]] as her default uniform. She also wears red [[wristband|wristbands]] and keeps a 20 mm Oerlikon anti-air gun on her right [[armlet]]. Her 76 mm single mount is holstered [i]on the side of the bikini itself[/i].

She is historically the submarine responsible for sinking [[Taihou (Azur Lane)|]] in the battle of the Philippine Sea, explaining why the latter is fearful of her in the game voice lines (and in [[Azur Lane: Slow Ahead]]).

title: achilles_(azur_lane)
body:
[[Azur Lane]]'s personification of the fifth [i]Leander[/i]-class light cruiser, HMS/HMNZS [i]Achilles[/i] (pennant number 70).

Historically built and commissioned under the [[Royal Navy]] before being transferred to New Zealand in 1941. In 1946, she was returned to the Royal Navy, who proceeded to sell her off to India two years later as HMIS/INS [i]Delhi[/i].

For her retrofit form, see her [[Achilles (retrofit) (azur lane)|corresponding page.]]

title: alfredo_oriani_(azur_lane)
body:
[i][[Azur Lane]][/i]'s personification of the Italian destroyer [i]Alfredo Oriani[/i]. Character designed by [[Namyo]]. 

She is portrayed in-game with [[long hair|long]] light [[brown hair]] tied to a [[ponytail]], and [[blue eyes]].

Her default outfit consists of a [[sleeveless]] [[white dress]] with gold fringe and her real-life hull letters "OA" printed on the skirt-side, [[sunglasses]], a [[black jacket]] with a red inner layer, a [[thigh strap]] to her right leg, [[white thighhighs]], [[knee boots]], a bag slung to her side, and a [[camera]].

Her [[rigging]] consists of her two historic 120 mm twin mounts, one on each side, and two 533 mm triple [[torpedo tubes]], one on each side.

h4. History
In real-life, she was the name ship of her class of four destroyers grouped under the 9th Destroyer Division, commissioned in 1937. She was also the only survivor of the four and saw post-war service with France until 1954.

title: grand_caster_(fate)
body:
The antagonist of the first arc of [[Fate/Grand Order]], responsible for the incineration of humanity. His true name is [[Solomon (Fate)|]].

[spoiler]In actuality, [[Goetia (Fate)|]] took the form of Solomon after his death and impersonated him. He can be distinguished from the true Solomon by the extra lines on his face and his front [[braid]] resembling a [[demon pillar (fate)|]].[/spoiler]

title: solomon_(fate)
body:
Antagonist from [[Fate/Grand Order]]. Designated as the [[Grand Caster (Fate)|]]. Created modern magecraft, ushering in the Age of Man, earning the name "King of Magic" for his feat.

[spoiler]Was the Caster in the Grand/Order universe's version of the 2004 Fuyuki Holy Grail War, and his Master was [[Marisbury Animusphere]]. After winning the war and granted a chance to make a wish to the Holy Grail, the Master wished for enough funds to complete the creation of Chaldea. For the Servant, a chance to live life as a normal human being i.e. [[Romani Archaman]]. Romani (the real Solomon) return his gifts to God (i.e. gave up his human life) at the climax of the first Grand Order to give the player a fighting chance to defeat [[Goetia (fate)|]] -- who had hijacked Solomon's body -- the real villain of the first Grand Order.[/spoiler]

title: shirayuki_(azur_lane)
body:
[[Azur Lane]]'s depiction of the Japanese destroyer [i]Shirayuki[/i]. Character design by [[Alisa (kuro no sakura)|]]. 

Bears an uncanny resemblance to [[Usada Pekora]] due to similar attributes as [[rabbit ears]], [[red eyes]], greyish [[white hair]] tied into twin braids, [[white dress]], and the presence of a white [[fur collar]] a la [[Don-chan (Usada Pekora)|]] and sentient bunnies a la [[Pekomon (usada pekora)|]].

There are striking differences, though, such as a [[black skirt]], [[long sleeves]], white [[thighhighs]], an [[oil-paper umbrella]], and the usual IJN rig of two 12.7 cm twin mounts and two 61 cm triple [[torpedo tubes]] with [[shimenawa]] and [[shide]].

In real life, [i]Shirayuki[/i] was the second [i]Fubuki[/i]-class destroyer built and saw action in the battles of Sunda Strait, [[battle of Midway|Midway]], and Naval Guadalcanal. She was later sunk in the battle of the Bismarck Sea in March 1943.

title: ned_flanders
body:
One of the many characters of the American animated comedy sitcom [[The Simpsons]].
The nice guy next door neighbor to the Simpson family. Originally, Ned was just a "better Christian" than [[homer simpson|Homer]], being affable, polite, intellectual, friendly, and sincerely religious. As the seasons went on, his "sweetness" and his religiosity grew until he became a byword for fanatical religious faith and doormat-like pleasantry. His being a doormat in the name of being nice to others faded. The religious zeal, however, remains. As of Season 29, he has taken over his late second wife's job as the fourth grade teacher; he previously served briefly as principal. At some point in Season 33, however, Ned was fired for praying on school grounds, and the job was given to Rayshelle Peyton. Voiced by Harry Shearer.

title: nelson_muntz
body:
One of the many characters of the [[united_states|American]] animated comedy sitcom [[The Simpsons]].
Originally the worst bully in Springfield Elementary, the closest thing Bart had to an archnemesis of his own age and the leader of Jimbo, Kearney and Dolph. As the seasons passed, though, he became more sympathetic and eventually began to clean up his act. As a result, his broken home started mending itself. Voiced by Nancy Cartwright.

title: dr._finkelstein
body: Dr. Finkelstein is a character and minor antagonist in Tim Burton's 1993 stop-motion Disney film [[The Nightmare Before Christmas]]. He is a wheelchair-bound mad scientist residing in Halloween Town, and the creator of Sally and Jewel Finkelstein. Throughout the film, he attempts to calm and restrain Sally against the outside world, while also helping [[Jack Skellington]] take Christmas. Too frustrated with his creation, Finkelstein abandons Sally and begins designing a new being, later revealed to be Jewel.

title: demae-can
body: Demae-can is a delivery portal site that only operates in Japan.

title: oogie_boogie
body: Oogie Boogie is the main antagonist of the 1993 stop-motion film [[The Nightmare Before Christmas]]. He is the infamous Boogeyman, depicted as a bug-filled burlap sack with a penchant for gambling. Oogie lives on the outskirts of Halloween Town, in a casino-like lair underneath the treehouse of his henchmen Lock, Shock, and Barrel. He is both feared and detested for his ghastly nature, cannibalistic appetite, and rivalry with the Pumpkin King, [[Jack Skellington]].

title: sally_(nbc)
body: Sally (Née Finklestein) is the deuteragonist of the film [[The Nightmare Before Christmas]], and the main protagonist of the novel Long Live The Pumpkin Queen. She is a rag doll from Halloween Town. Intelligent, yet inconspicuous, she longs for independence, but is repeatedly restrained by Doctor Finklestein, her overprotective creator, and also is romantically infatuated with [[Jack Skellington]], the Pumpkin King.

title: beetlejuice
body:
Beetlejuice is an American dark fantasy horror comedy media franchise that originated with the film Beetlejuice (1988). 
The film was directed by Tim Burton from a screenplay by Michael McDowell and Warren Skaaren. The film stars Alec Baldwin, Geena Davis, Winona Ryder, and [[Michael Keaton]] as the title character.
The story follows Barbara and Adam Maitland, a loving young couple who die in a car accident and find themselves caught in the Celestial Bureaucracy of the afterlife. Unable to move on, they haunt their rustic Connecticut home until it's bought by Charles and Delia Deetz, an insufferable yuppie couple with a goth daughter, [[lydia deetz|Lydia]]. Wishing to rid themselves of the Deetzes, they enlist the help of a malevolent ghost named Betelgeuse (pronounced Beetlejuice) to drive them out. But between Betelgeuse’s unwillingness to play fair and the increasingly strong bond between Lydia and the Maitlands, who come to see her as the daughter they never got to have, things go off the rails quickly.

The film is remembered for its dark humor and inventive visuals, helping to make Burton a household name. The score by Danny Elfman and a memorable musical sequence set to Harry Belafonte's "Day-O (The Banana Boat Song)" also brought renewed attention to both performers.

In the years since its release, Beetlejuice spawned a franchise, including a late '80s-early '90s [[Beetlejuice (cartoon)|animated series of the same name]], a theatrical production that commenced in 2018, and a film sequel, [[Beetlejuice Beetlejuice]], released in 2024.

H6.See also

* [[Beetlejuice (Cartoon)]]

title: oni
body:
A creature from Japanese folklore. Usually translated as "demon" or "[[ogre]]".

Traditionally depicted with [[red skin|red]] or [[blue skin]], a [[tiger print]] [[loincloth]], and [[horns]]. Oni horns can be depicted in various ways, whether it be as long, smooth, [[skin-covered horns|skin-covered]] or otherwise the same color as the skin, located on the forehead; or [[cone horns|cone-shaped]] in any number of colors, whether it be white, grey, yellow, etc. atop their head. Their weapon of choice is the [[spiked club]], particularly the [[kanabou]]. They are violent and favor brawn over brains.

Save for the horns, modern depictions tend to mute these characteristics considerably or entirely, especially in female characters, only keeping their iconic dual horns intact.

Oni are commonly associated with [[Setsubun]], a holiday taking place on February 3rd, the last day of winter in the traditional Japanese calendar. On this day it is tradition to throw roasted soybeans in order to drive away oni; this practice is known as [[mamemaki]].

Typical examples of oni are [[Lum]], [[Gedomaru]], [[Ibuki Suika]] and [[Hoshiguma Yuugi]].

title: ootani_shouhei
body: Ootani Shouhei (大谷 翔平, born July 5, 1994) is a Japanese professional baseball pitcher and designated hitter. Ootani played for the [[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]] from 2013-2017 and made his MLB debut in 2018 with the [[Los Angeles Angels]]. From the 2024 season he is signed to play for the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]], after signing an unprecedented 700 million USD contract with the team.

title: hanshin_tigers
body:
Japanese [[baseball]] team, based in Osaka and playing in the Central League of Nippon Professional Baseball. The team is one of the most popular in Japan along with the rival [[Yomiuri Giants]], and is often compared to the [[Boston Red Sox]] of Major League Baseball in terms of history and fan support.

Infamously is the subject of the ""Curse of the Colonel":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Curse_of_the_Colonel]", where Tigers supporters throwing a statue of [[Colonel Sanders]] into a river after the team's 1985 Japan Series victory has been attributed to a two-decade long drought of the Tigers not winning the Central League championship and their almost-40-year Japan Series drought. The curse was seen as broken following the Tigers' victory in the 2023 Japan Series.

body:
Florida is a state in the [[United States]], located on a peninsula in the south-eastern corner of the country. Particularly known for it's year-round hot weather, [[palm tree]]s, and [[alligator]]s. It is also the location of [[NASA]]'s Kennedy Space Center, where most US rocket launches take place.

The state is particularly notorious in [[meme]] culture for "Florida Man" headlines, which describe bizarre (and usually drug-induced) crimes committed by Floridians.

title: matsui_hideki
body:
(松井 秀喜 [i]Matsui Hideki[/i], born June 12, 1974), nicknamed "[b]Godzilla[/b]"

A Japanese former professional baseball outfielder and designated hitter. He batted left-handed and threw right-handed.

After playing the first ten seasons of his career for the [[Yomiuri Giants]] of Nippon Professional Baseball, he played the next seven seasons, from 2003–2009, for the [[New York Yankees]] of Major League Baseball. As a free agent, Matsui then had one-year stints with the [[Los Angeles Angels]] of Anaheim, the [[Oakland Athletics]], and the [[Tampa Bay Rays]].

Matsui was successful in both leagues, winning the Central League Most Valuable Player Award three times in NPB (1996, 2000 & 2002), as well as the 2009 World Series Most Valuable Player Award in MLB. On July 28, 2013, Matsui signed a one-day minor league contract with the New York Yankees in order to officially retire as a Yankee.

title: suzuki_ichirou
body:
(鈴木 一朗 [i]Suzuki Ichirō[/i], born October 22, 1973)

Sometimes simply known as Ichiro (イチロー).

A Japanese former professional baseball outfielder. He began his career in 1992 playing for the [[Orix Buffaloes]] (then the Orix BlueWave) of Nippon Professional Baseball before joining Major League Baseball in 2000, starting with the [[Seattle Mariners]] and staying with them until 2012. Suzuki spent two seasons each with the [[New York Yankees]] and the [[Miami Marlins]] before finishing out his career as a Mariner in 2018. He officially retired on March 21, 2019.

He had a unique ritual of holding his bat upright at arm's length, and tugging at his sleeve before getting set for each pitch.

title: tag_group:focus_tags
body:
[See [[tag groups]].]

Used to tag artwork that focuses on a particular element. Multiple can be used.

If the element is the only thing in the image, a focus tag should still be used, with the exception of [[solo focus]], where [[solo]] should be used instead.
For example, an image with only boys still has a [[male focus]].

The plural of focus is [i]foci[/i].

title: bigro
body:
A fictional manned giant robot from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse. It first appeared in the original [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] anime TV series from 1979.

[b]MA-05 Bigro[/b]

A anti-warship [[mobile armor]] fielded by the Principality of [[Zeon]] during [[mobile_suit_gundam|The One Year War]], it was a fearsome and fast mobile-weapon capable of not only sinking battleships in one shot of its mega-particle cannon but also tearing apart any other smaller targets with its large manipulator claws. It was also armed with a fourtube missle launcher as well in later units powerful gatling cannons to round out its impressively destructive arsenal.

title: daryl_lorenz
body:
A fictional character from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse. He first appeared in [[Gundam Thunderbolt]].

[b]Daryl Lorenz[/b] is an [[amputee]] and [[Zeon]] pilot of the [[Zaku II (Reuse P Device)]].

title: zaku_ii_(reuse_p_device)
body:
A fictional manned giant robot from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse. It first appeared in [[Gundam Thunderbolt]].

[b]MS-06R Zaku II High Mobility Type (Reuse P Device)[/b]

A thorough series of upgrades to the [[Zaku II]] High Mobility Type [[mobile_suit|MS]], the most notable of which a huge set of added boosters, twin bazookas, twin [[machine gun]]s and countless manipulator arms to wield the extra armament. 

It was piloted by [[Daryl Lorenz]]  - however, the unit's performance literally cost him an arm and a leg, as the [b]Reuse Psycho Device[/b] which enabled him to control it required the amputation of all of his remaining limbs. Because of this the unit is sometimes called the [b]Psycho Zaku[/b].
other_names: リユース・P・デバイス装備高機動型ザク

title: skullgirls
body:
Skullgirls is a independent 2D [[fighting game]] developed by Reverge Labs and published by Autumn Games. The series' co-creator and art director is [[Alex Ahad]] (aka [b]o_8[/b]/[b]Oh8[/b]). The setting of the game revolves around the "Skull Heart", an artifact which grants wishes for women. title: e6_komachi
body:
Formerly known as "Super Komachi". The E6 series (E6系) is a Japanese [[Shinkansen]] [[high-speed train]] type operated by [[East Japan Railway Company]] ([[East Japan Railway Company|JR East]]) on Komachi "mini-shinkansen" (Shinkansen on non-high-speed line) (services on the Tōhoku Shinkansen and Akita Shinkansen from Tokyo to Akita since 16 March 2013. A pre-series set was delivered in June 2010 for extensive testing, with 23 full-production sets delivered between November 2012 and spring 2014

The 7-car [[e6_komachi|E6 series]] trains operate in conjunction with [[E5 Hayabusa|E5 series]] or [[H5 Hayabusa|H5 series]] (since March 2016) 10-car trains, initially on just four return services daily from 16 March 2013. They replaced all of the previous [[E3 Tsubasa|E3 series]] trains on Komachi services by 15 March 2014.

H4. Examples 

* !asset #23642147: Shinkansen E6 Komachi 
* !asset #23524668: [[E5 Hayabusa]] Coupled together with [[E6 Komachi]]
* !asset #23642157: [[E5 Hayabusa]] Coupled together with [[E6 Komachi]]
* !asset #23642169: Shinkansen E6 Komachi Coupling with [[E5 Hayabusa]]

title: mash_kyrielight_(dangerous_beast)_(cosplay)
body:
Originally an [[Fate/Grand Order|F/GO]] [[mash kyrielight (dangerous beast)|Craft Essence]] released during Halloween showing [[Mash Kyrielight]] in skimpy, wolf-inspired, [[revealing clothes]] with a [[fur trim]]. The outfit immediately caught on inspiring artists to draw other Fate characters in the costume and official merchandise like figures to be made of Mash replicating the card art. Due to the enormous popularity it has become commonplace to draw [[cosplay|many characters]] in the "Dangerous Beast" (デンジャラス・ビースト) tag regardless of their connection to the series. 

h4. See also

* post #2518353: the original art 
* [[Huttslayer Leia]]

body: Víctor González Torres (born July 1, 1947, in [[Mexico City]]) is a Mexican pharmaceutical businessman and politician, popularly known as Doctor Simi, the name of the character that represents his chain of companies, collectively called Farmacias Similares. title: ramrod
body: A ramrod is a stick that has a wide end, used for muzzle-loaded [[antique_firearm]]s such as [[musket]]s, [[arquebus]]s, or even [[cannon]]s, to push the projectile up against the propellant (mainly blackpowder) down away from the muzzle, toward the end of the weapon's barrel to be ready to fire. A gun's ramrods can found on and usually held in a notch underneath the barrel.

title: arquebus
body:
It is a forerunner of the rifle and other longarm firearms.
Also known as a  "hagbut", it was a portable long-barrelled gun dating from the 15th century: fired by a [[wheellock]] or [[matchlock]] mechanism. The Japanese model, first imported from Portugal in 1543, was known as the [[tanegashima]].

h4.See also

* "Wikipedia article":http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arquebus

title: racetrack
body:
A purpose-built course for [[car]] or [[horse]] [[racing]], usually with seating for fans to watch. For the type of track used for track and field events, see [[running track]].

Motorsport tracks are typically paved, though dirt tracks for rallycross, motocross, and certain stock cars are also used. Horse racing tracks are always dirt-based.

title: sheffy_(princess_connect!)
body:
A character from [[Princess Connect!]] and Princess Connect! Re:Dive. She is a member of the guild Gourmet Edifice.

She is a [[dragon girl]] who has [[purple eyes]], [[blue horns|blue]] [[dragon horns]], [[small breasts]], and [[long hair|long]] [[light blue hair]] stylized in a [[single braid]] with [[bangs]], an [[ahoge]] & [[hair between eyes]]. As well as [[blue wings|blue]] [[dragon wings]] and a [[dragon tail]]. She wears a [[sleeveless dress|sleeveless]] [[white dress]], [[open coat|open]] [[fur-trimmed coat|fur-trimmed]] [[white coat]], [[black gloves|black]] [[fur-trimmed gloves]], and [[pantyhose]].

[spoiler]Her name in the real world before the events of Re:Dive was [[Sheffy (real) (princess connect!)|Agato Shifuna]] (阿賀斗 紫布菜).[/spoiler]

She is voiced by [[Kondou Reina]].

title: l'origine_du_monde
body: [i]L'Origine du monde ("The Origin of the World") is a picture painted in oil on canvas by the French painter Gustave Courbet in 1866. It is a close-up view of the vulva and abdomen of a naked woman (Joanna Hiffernan, the lover of Courbet's friend James Whistler, an American painter), lying on a bed with legs spread.[/i] - "Wikipedia":[https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=L%27Origine_du_monde&oldid=1253488024]

body:
[b]HAL 9000[/b] is a character in [[Arthur C. Clarke]]'s Space Odyssey [[Science fiction]] series. 

It first appeared in [[2001 A Space Odyssey]], where HAL ([b]H[/b]euristically programmed [b]AL[/b]gorithmic computer) is an artificial intelligence that controls the systems of the [[Discovery One]] [[spacecraft]] and interacts with the ship's [[astronaut]] crew. Being a computer, HAL has no distinct physical form, though is visually represented as a red television camera eye located on equipment panels throughout the ship.

HAL 9000 is voiced by Douglas Rain in the two film adaptations of the Space Odyssey series. HAL speaks in a soft, calm voice and a conversational manner, in contrast to the crewmen, [[Dave Bowman]] and [[Frank Poole]], who speak tersely and with little emotional inflection.

HAL became operational on 12 January 1997 at the HAL Laboratories in Urbana, Illinois as production number 3; in the film 2001, the activation year was 1992 and 1991 in earlier screenplays. In addition to maintaining the Discovery One spacecraft systems during the interplanetary mission to [[Jupiter (planet)|]] (or [[Saturn (planet)|]] as in the original novel, published shortly after the release of the film), HAL is capable of speech, speech recognition, facial recognition, natural language processing, lip reading, art appreciation, interpreting and reproducing emotional behaviours, reasoning, and playing chess.

title: cinco_de_mayo
body:
Cinco de Mayo is an annual celebration held on May 5 to celebrate Mexico's victory over the Second French Empire at the Battle of Puebla in 1862, led by General Ignacio Zaragoza. Zaragoza died months after the battle from an illness, however, and a larger French force ultimately defeated the Mexican army at the Second Battle of Puebla and then occupied [[Mexico City]].
More popular in the [[United States]] than in [[Mexico]], Cinco de Mayo has become associated with the celebration of Mexican-American culture.

body: Fish Hooks is an American animated television series created by Noah Z. Jones and developed by Alex Hirsch and William Reiss for [[disney|Disney Channel]]. The show ran for three seasons from September 3, 2010 to April 4, 2014, airing a total of 59 episodes.

title: justin_roiland_(person)
body: Mark Justin Roiland (born February 21, 1980) is an American voice actor, animator, writer, and producer. He co-created the Adult Swim animated sitcom [[Rick and Morty]], for which he voiced the protagonists [[Rick Sanchez]] and [[Morty Smith]] in seasons 1 through 6 from 2013 to 2022, as well as Hulu's [[Solar Opposites]], in which he voiced the main character, Korvo, in seasons 1 through 3 from 2020 to 2022, until both networks severed ties with him in 2023. He had also voiced Earl of Lemongrab in [[Adventure Time]], Blendin Blandin in [[Gravity Falls]], and Oscar in [[Fish Hooks]]. He founded the animation studio Justin Roiland's Solo Vanity Card Productions! and the video game studio Squanch Games, though he resigned from the latter in 2023.

title: nicolas_maduro
body: Nicolás Maduro Moros (born 23 November 1962) is a Venezuelan politician and the 53rd president of [[Venezuela]] since 2013. Previously, he was the 24th vice president of Venezuela from 2012 to 2013, the minister of foreign affairs from 2006 to 2012, and the 3rd president of the National Assembly of Venezuela from 2005 to 2006.

title: the_girl_with_the_dragon_tattoo
body:
[b]The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo[/b] (original title in Swedish: Män som hatar kvinnor – literally, men who hate women) is a crime novel by the late [[Sweden|Swedish]] author and journalist Stieg Larsson. It is the first book of the "Millennium series" trilogy, which, when published posthumously in 2005, became a best-seller in Europe and the United States.

The Swedish film production company Yellow Bird created film versions of the Millennium Trilogy, all released in 2009, beginning with The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo, directed by Danish filmmaker Niels Arden Oplev. The protagonists were played by Michael Nyqvist and [[Noomi Rapace]]. 

A Hollywood adaptation of the book, directed by David Fincher and with a musical score by Trent Reznor of [[Nine Inch Nails]] was released in December 2011. The main characters were portrayed by Daniel Craig and [[Rooney Mara]]. The score by Reznor won the 2013 Grammy Award for Best Score Soundtrack for Visual Media. 

h4. See also

* [[Lisbeth Salander]]

body:
[b]MTV[/b] (Music Television) is cable music channel that began airing in August 1, 1981. While the channel originally aired music videos from rock bands, the channel later aired music videos of different music genres after criticism by some artists like [[Michael Jackson]] for the channels lack of diversity  especially the lack of black singers. 

Since MTV's airing, the channel not only airs music videos but also music documentaries, biographies of famous singers, live concerts, award shows and even original content that isn't music related like adult animation, game shows and reality shows .

title: cutlery
body:
Cutlery refers to handheld tools used for the consumption of food, often found in Western tables and comprises forks, spoons, knives, and other similar utensils, such as sporks.

While often used interchangeably with utensils, utensils cover a larger range of tools (such as ladles), where cutlery more specifically refers to items you’d find on a dining table.

title: outie_navel
body:
A belly button ([[navel]]) that outwardly protrudes from the belly of the character/person.

The inverse being an "innie" navel (where it appears to be sunken in a small pit on the belly).

Most often seen on pregnant women as the growing womb pushes on and out the navel from the inside, especially during middle to late stages of pregnancy. Can also be seen on males and non-pregnant females as well, generally associated with either non-pregnancy related belly expansion/inflation, or just how the belly button had ended up since the belly button (navel) is formed from the child side remains of the umbilical cord after birth and the cutting of said cord.

title: tonberry
body:
Recurring enemy in the [[Final Fantasy]] series by [[Square Enix]].

Generally lizard-like in appearance with beady yellow eyes, an aquatic tail, a draping cloak, and, most notably, a [[lantern]] and [[knife|butcher knife]] in either hand.

With its high HP, its trademark attack pattern is to slowly move in to the party and instant-death [[stab]] a character, making a *doink* sound.

title: fischl_(genshin_impact)
body:
[[Genshin Impact]] character.

A mysterious girl who calls herself "Prinzessin der Verurteilung" and travels with a night [[crow]] named [[Oz (genshin impact)|]].
Currently serves as an investigator in the Adventurers' Guild.

Through her unique abilities, [[chuunibyou]] personality, and (while she would never admit it herself) hard work, Fischl has become a rising star among the Adventurers' Guild's investigators, earning the recognition of all.

She has a petite build, light [[green eyes]], [[small breasts]], and [[blonde hair|blonde]] [[two side up]] hair with a [[black ribbon|black]] bat-winged [[hair ribbon]]. She wears a black [[eyepatch]] to not obstruct her view when possessing Oz.

Overall, Fischl seems to have designed her outfit to be as asymmetrical as physically possible. She wears a sleeveless black lace dress-like [[leotard]] with a black lace [[collar]] and [[purple bowtie]], crosses stitched in, and black and violet [[tailcoat]]s. Her [[vision (genshin impact)|]] is tied to the back of this dress with a bat wing-style [[purple ribbon]]. She wears a shoulder-length black [[gloves|glove]] on her left hand and a black and purple [[single_sleeve|sleeve]] or [[single bridal gauntlet]] on her right arm. She wears a transparent black [[single_thighhigh|thighhigh]] on her right leg and a similar thigh-high black sock held up by [[garter straps]] on her left. She wears [[black_footwear|black]] [[boots]] with a light purple lining, gold [[high_heels|heels]], and [[bat_ornament|bat wing decorations]].

In general, Fischl seems to style herself after the titular character of said book "Flowers for Princess Fischl".

Her full name is Fischl von Luftschloss Narfidort. Actual name: Amy.

She also appears in [[Honkai Impact 3rd]] as a playable character.

Chinese CV: Mace
Japanese CV: [[Uchida Maaya]]

title: hasshaku-sama
body:
[b]Hasshaku-sama[/b] (八尺様, lit. "Ms. Eight-feet-tall") is the titular monster of a 2008 fictional ghost story that was posted in "Let's gather up seriously, deadly scary stories, shall we? (死ぬ程洒落にならない怖い話を集めてみない?)" thread/topic of [[2channel]]'s Occult Board. This is regarded as  one of the best stories in the thread. 

Essentially a female [[Slender man]], she stalks and kills (or rapes) her young targets when they're out in the open space after seeing her tall visage. She makes her presence known with her signature laugh "Po, po, po..." with a somewhat masculine voice.

Her usual depiction is a [[tall female|tall woman]] with [[large breasts|large]] to [[huge breasts]] with [[long hair|long]], [[black hair]]. She's usually depicted wearing a [[white dress|white]] [[sundress]] and a [[sun hat]].

h4. See also

title: gwyn_lord_of_cinder
body:
[b]Gwyn, Lord of Cinder[/b] is the main antagonist and final boss of the video game [[Dark Souls I]].

He was once one of the wielders of the First Flame and one of the founders of the Age of Fire, but due to the aforementioned Flame dwindling over time, he sacrificed himself to preserve its lifespan, thus beginning the tradition of soul-sacrifice to extend the Age of Fire.

title: kirby's_return_to_dream_land_deluxe
body:
The remake of [[Kirby's Return to Dream Land]], released on February 24th, 2023 for the [[Nintendo Switch]] as a late celebration of [i][[kirby_(series)|Kirby's]][/i] 30th anniversary. A digital Demo was released earlier that month, on February 8th.

h4. Notable additions
* Graphical overhaul.
* All playable characters can emote using the right control stick.
* Helper Magolor, an easier difficulty that grants extra items and helps against bottomless pits.
* Two new copy abilities: [[sand kirby|Sand]] and [[mecha kirby|Mecha]], and the return of [[festival kirby|Festival]].
* Merry Magoland: a new area run by [[Magolor]] with multiple mini-games from previous [i]Kirby[/i] games (plus two new ones), all playable with up to 4 players.
* [[magolor epilogue|Magolor Epilogue: The Interdimensional Traveler]], an all-new extra mode that features a playable Magolor after the main game's events.
* [[Kirby]]'s friends all gain extra moves first seen in [[Kirby: Star Allies]].
* [spoiler] [[Magolor Soul]] becomes way more powerful in The True Arena [/spoiler]

h4. Other changes
* [[King Dedede]] receives a re-design, not unlike the one seen in [[Kirby and the Forgotten Land]]
* [[Bandana Waddle Dee]] is now fully referred as such (in the original, it was only "[[Waddle Dee]]"), and the once red cloth at the tip of his spear is now yellow, as seen in other modern releases.
* Characters can wear Dress-Up Masks based on multiple characters from across the [[kirby (series)|series]].
* The Super Abilities used by Kirby are generally made faster.
* All bosses now have special Pause screen descriptions.
* Certain events in the game have different music. A few notable examples:
** The mid-boss tower in the fifth stage of Nutty Noon, if Kirby takes the secret entrance.
** [[HR-D3]]'s second phase using "Roar of Dedede" from [[Kirby and the Forgotten Land]].
** [spoiler] [[Magolor Soul]] using "Super Ruler's Coronation - OVERLORD" from [[Kirby: Star Allies]] in The True Arena.[/spoiler]

h4. External links
* "Official website":https://kirbysreturntodreamlanddeluxe.nintendo.com/
* "Official website (UK)":https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/Nintendo-Switch-games/Kirby-s-Return-to-Dream-Land-Deluxe-2267334.html

* "WiKirby: Kirby's Return to Dream Land Deluxe":https://wikirby.com/wiki/Kirby%27s_Return_to_Dream_Land_Deluxe

title: galaxia_(sword)
body:
[[Meta Knight]]'s trademark [[sword]] in the [i][[Kirby (series)|]][/i] video game series, also appearing in the anime [i][[Kirby: Right Back At Ya]][/i] and the [i][[Super Smash Bros.]][/i] games. It has a golden blade with 4-6 spikes (2-3 on each side) and a ruby-colored pommel stone on its hilt.

In the games, Meta Knight is capable of summoning tornadoes and sword beams with it, but in the anime adaptation, it is a separate entity with a mind of its own. As a sentient being, Galaxia will only allow those with pure intentions to touch it; otherwise, they will be electrocuted and/or killed. The only known character besides Meta Knight that is capable of wielding Galaxia is [[Kirby]].

In [i][[Kirby and the Amazing Mirror]][/i], Meta Knight wields a sword called the Master, or the Master Sword. It reuses the appearance of the Galaxia in Meta Knight's sprites and [[official art]], though in other artwork its appearance varies. It is unconfirmed whether or not these are the same sword, or if "Master" is merely the name of the [[copy ability]] Kirby gains while wielding it.

[spoilers][[Magolor Soul]] and [[Void Termina]] can use giant swords closely resembling Galaxia in their boss fights, which raises more questions than answers.[/spoilers]

title: akashi_(azur_lane)
body:
[[Azur Lane]]'s personification of Japanese Repair Ship [i]Akashi[/i] (明石).

In her base art, she is a [[cat girl]] with [[green hair|green]] [[very long hair]] and an [[ahoge]]. She has a [[mole under eye|mole under her]] [[yellow eyes]]. On her neck is a [[red ribbon|red]] [[ribbon choker|ribbon]], [[neck bell|bell]] [[choker]]. She wears a [[double-breasted]] [[white dress]], with a [[sailor collar]] and [[sleeves past wrists|sleeves past her wrists]], with [[tools]] coming out of her wrist. Her [[rigging]] is composed of a giant [[wrench]] and a [[crane_(machine)|mechanical crane]].

In game, she appears as both an obtainable unit and the premium store owner. Since players must interact with her whenever they wish to purchase the premium currency ([[gem (azur lane)|gems]]) with real money, she's portrayed as very greedy in her fanwork.

Voiced by [[Uesaka Sumire]].

title: hakuryuu_(azur_lane)
body:
[i][[Azur Lane]][/i]'s personification of the aircraft carrier [i]Hakuryuu[/i], as part of a collaboration with [i][[World of Warships]][/i]. 
Character design by [[Izuru (timbermetal)|]], voiced by [[Satou Satomi]]. 

She is portrayed with [[long hair|long]] [[grey hair]], [[grey eyes]], [[large breasts]], and [[mismatched horns]] with her left pointed up and right pointed to the side.

Her default outfit consists of a [[black dress|black]] [[pleated dress]] with a [[side slit]], [[black jacket]], [[black gloves]], [[thigh strap]]s, and [[knee pads]]. Her [[rigging]] is a split [[flight deck]] in an animalistic style containing her 100 mm twin [[anti-aircraft gun|DP mounts]] while she uses an [[huge weapon|oversized]] [[ootachi]] as her melee weapon.

In Azur Lane, she initially behaves in a stereotypical [[sukeban]] manner, often wielding her sword and trying to strike intimidating poses. However, she's actually an air-headed girl who only wants to look cool and is easily flustered, especially if she's without her katana. 

h4. Skins

* !post #4627907: Default
* !post #5018478: [[hakuryuu (slice dice and serve) (azur lane)|Slice, Dice, and Serve]]
* !post #6682511: [[hakuryuu (flash of silk and strings) (azur lane)|Flash of Silk and Strings]]
* !post #8207689: [[hakuryuu (folded over a thousand times) (azur lane)|Folded Over a Thousand Times]]

h4. History
She is based off the Project G15 "Taihō-Kai", an attempt by Japanese designers to create a successor to the [[taihou_(azur_lane)|infamously flawed carrier]]. She was to be larger, better armed, better protected, carry a larger air group, and would've corrected the numerous vulnerabilities found in her predecessor's design. Seven of the class were ordered and set to begin construction between 1944 and 1945 with expected completion dates between 1947 and 1948. Not one would be laid down before Japan's surrender.


h4. External links
* "Japanese Wikipedia: Project G15/[i]Taihou[/i]-kai":[https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E6%94%B9%E5%A4%A7%E9%B3%B3%E5%9E%8B%E8%88%AA%E7%A9%BA%E6%AF%8D%E8%89%A6]

body:

Unlike her sister ships that were released through monthly large-scale events, Bristol was released as part of the game's 2022 server player co-op event.
Like her other sisters, her character design is done by [[Nagu]].

She is portrayed with [[short hair|short]] [[black hair]] and [[brown eyes]] with [[glasses]]. Her default outfit consists of a black [[beret]], [[long sleeves|long-sleeved]] [[white shirt]], a [[sleeveless]] [[black dress]], [[green necktie]], black [[socks]], and black [[shoes]].

title: tim_curry
body:
Timothy James Curry (born 19 April 1946) is an English actor and singer. He rose to prominence as [[Dr. Frank-N-Furter]] in the film [[The Rocky Horror Picture Show]] (1975), reprising the role he had originated in the 1973 London, 1974 Los Angeles, and 1975 Broadway musical stage productions of The Rocky Horror Show.

Curry received further acclaim for his film and television roles, including Rooster Hannigan in the film adaptation of Annie (1982), Darkness in Legend (1985), Wadsworth in Clue (1985), [[Pennywise]] in the miniseries It (1990), the Concierge in Home Alone 2: Lost in New York (1992), and Long John Silver in Muppet Treasure Island (1996).
