title: over_the_garden_wall
body: Over the Garden Wall is an American animated television miniseries created by Patrick McHale for [[Cartoon Network]]. The series centers on two half-brothers who travel through a mysterious [[forest]] to find their way home, encountering a variety of strange and fantastical things on their journey. The show is based on McHale's animated short film Tome of the Unknown, which was produced as part of Cartoon Network Studios' shorts development program. [[Elijah Wood]] and Collin Dean voice the protagonists Wirt and Greg, and Melanie Lynskey voices Beatrice, a bluebird. The series' voice cast also includes Christopher Lloyd, [[Tim Curry]], Bebe Neuwirth, Chris Isaak, Shirley Jones, Thomas Lennon, Jack Jones, Jerron Paxton, John Cleese and Samuel Ramey. The Blasting Company composed the soundtrack. Over the Garden Wall was broadcast throughout the week of November 3 to November 7, 2014.

title: pyramid_head
body:
Enemy from [[Silent Hill 2]]. He attacks [[James Sunderland]] several times across the game, but cannot be defeated until near the end of the game. Notably, there are two scenes in the game where he appears to be raping other monsters.

He takes the appearance of male figure wearing a pyramidal helmet way too large to be possibly worn by a human, and he's armed with an [[great knife|absurdly large knife]].

Pyramid Head became the most iconic monster of the Silent Hill franchise due to its intimidating appearance and constant stalking of the player. He appeared in the Silent Hill movie and inspired very similar monsters in later Silent Hill games. The fanbase is known to reference his propensity for rape.

[spoiler]Pyramid Head is presumed to be a manifestation of James' guilt and desire for punishment for the crimes he commited.[/spoiler]

title: pavel_chekov
body:
Pavel Andreievich Chekov (Russian: Павел Андреевич Чехов) is a fictional character in the [[Star Trek]] universe.
He is the ship's navigator from Season 2 onwards. Chekov had a tendency to refer to [[russia|Glorious Mother Russia]] and claim that any human advancement, be it technological or cultural, originated there. He also had terrible luck and frequently ran foul of whatever physical or psychological menace the ship was facing that week, mainly because Walter Koenig had an excellent capacity for screaming. Aside from that, he and [[hikaru sulu|Sulu]] were good friends and would frequently banter about the action.

Chekov is, by far, the most junior of the regular bridge officers, but the writers justified his presence by having him act as the relief science officer whenever [[Spock]] was busy or incapacitated. In fact, Chekov would often abandon his navigation console in order to take up the science scanner if Spock had to step away, even at warp or in the middle of a battle. In Star Trek III: The Search for Spock, in a nod to this, Chekov identifies himself as the "Acting Science Officer" of the Enterprise.

title: james_doohan
body: James Montgomery Doohan (/ˈduːən/; March 3, 1920 – July 20, 2005) was a Canadian actor, best known for his role as [[Montgomery scott|Montgomery "Scotty" Scott]] in the television and film series [[Star Trek]]. Doohan's characterization of the Scottish chief engineer of the Starship Enterprise has become one of the most recognizable elements in the Star Trek franchise, and inspired many fans to pursue careers in engineering and other technical fields. He also made contributions behind the scenes, such as the initial development of the [[Klingon]] and [[Vulcan]] languages.

title: nyota_uhura
body: Nyota Uhura (/niˈoʊtə ʊˈhʊrə/), or simply Uhura, is a fictional character in the [[Star Trek]] franchise. In the [[star trek: the original series|original television series]], the character was portrayed by [[Nichelle Nichols]], who reprised the role for the first six Star Trek feature films. A younger Uhura is portrayed by Celia Rose Gooding in the 2022 prequel series [[Star Trek: Strange New Worlds]], while an alternate timeline version of Uhura has been portrayed by actress Zoe Saldaña in the feature films [[Star Trek (2009)]], Star Trek Into Darkness (2013), and [[Star Trek: Beyond]] (2016).

title: shadowheart_(baldur's_gate)
body:
One of the eight Origin characters in [[Baldur's Gate 3]] who can either be the player character or potential party member. An half-elf cleric of Shar, the goddess of darkness and loss. She was tasked to bring an artifact back to her cult, though she was stripped of her memories along with her true name. Despite her devotion to Shar, Shadowheart is surprisingly empathetic, being fond of children and having fewer qualms in providing assistance to others.

[spoilers]If pushed to go against Shar, Shadowheart will learn the truth of her origins: Shadowheart wasn't raised to be a Sharran acolyte, but was born to and raised by worshippers of Selune, the goddess of the moon. She and her parents were kidnapped by Shar's zealots, with Shadowheart's memories being taken so that she could be molded into Shar's perfect champion. [/spoilers]

title: lae'zel
body:
One of the eight Origin characters in [[Baldur's Gate 3]] who can either be the player character or potential party member. A female githyanki fighter who is driven by ambition and fanatical loyalty to Vlaakith, the lich queen of the githyanki race. Notable for being the first Origin character the player will always meet, assuming she isn't the player character, of course. Like most githyanki, Lae'zel is proud, militaristic, and xenophobic, prioritizing her survival and goals, seeing the party as simply means to her ends, and looking down on concepts of the mortal plane such as empathy and altruism. She nonetheless recognizes and respects her companions capabilities, so long as they don't interfere with her goals.

Lae'zel has also become notorious for how bafflingly easy it is to win her affections and trigger an intimate relationship with, with one player having infamously speedrun from a new game to her intimate scene in as little as 2 minutes.

title: deanna_troi
body: Deanna Troi is a main character in the science-fiction television series [[Star Trek: The Next Generation]] and related TV series and films, portrayed by English actress Marina Sirtis. Troi is half-human, half-Betazoid, and has the psionic ability to sense emotions. She serves as the ship's counsellor on USS Enterprise-D. Throughout most of the series, she holds the rank of lieutenant commander. In the seventh season, Troi takes the bridge officer's examination and is promoted to the rank of commander, but continues as counsellor.

title: geordi_la_forge
body: Geordi La Forge[a] (/ˈdʒɔːrdi lə ˈfɔːrdʒ/ JOR-dee lə FORJ) is a fictional character who appeared in all seven seasons of the American science fiction television series [[Star Trek: The Next Generation]] and its four feature films as well as the third season of [[Star Trek: Picard]]. Portrayed by LeVar Burton, he served as helmsman of the USS Enterprise-D in the first season of The Next Generation, then occupied the role of the chief engineer for the rest of the series and in the films before appearing as a commodore in Picard. La Forge has been blind since his birth and uses technological devices that allow him to see – a VISOR in the series and the first film, replaced by ocular prosthetic implants in the last three films and in Picard.

title: worf_(star_trek)
body: Worf, son of Mogh is a fictional character in the [[Star Trek]] franchise, portrayed by actor Michael Dorn. He appears in the television series [[Star Trek: The Next Generation]] (TNG), seasons four through seven of [[Star Trek: Deep Space Nine]] (DS9), and the third and final season of [[Star Trek: Picard]], as well as the feature films Star Trek Generations (1994), Star Trek: First Contact (1996), Star Trek: Insurrection (1998), and Star Trek: Nemesis (2002).

He is the husband of Deanna Troi.

title: vivy
body:
Vivy, better known within the series as Diva, is the main protagonist of [[Vivy: Fluorite Eye's Song]]. She is an [[android]] that possesses [[very long hair|very long]] [[blue hair]] with an [[ahoge]], [[blue eyes]], and on the left side of her neck a glowing circle with an inverted triangle that is indicative of androids within the series.

Diva is a songstress AI and was the first autonomous humanoid AI. She was given the mission to make everyone happy through her singing, though she struggles at grasping how to accomplish that. Diva's first fan, a young girl named [[Kirishima Momoka]], gives her the nickname Vivy after the princess in a children's picture book who looks like Diva. Shortly before Diva's first birthday she meets the future AI [[Matsumoto (Vivy)|]], who takes control of the body of the teddy bear that Momoka gave Diva as a birthday present.

title: yama_no_susume
body:
[[Mountain]]-climbing themed manga series by [[shiro (octet)|Shiro]].

The series follows Yukimura Aoi after she has entered high school.  She reunites with a childhood friend, Kuraue Hinata, who she hasn't seen since elementary school.  Hinata is surprised to see how much Aoi has changed, as Aoi has become the complete opposite of what she was like in elementary school.  Aoi had an accident where she broke her leg from falling on the playground, which lead to her changes.  Hinata helps to encourage Aoi to rekindle her childhood interest in mountain climbing.

h4. Characters

* [[Yukimura Aoi]]
* [[Kuraue Hinata]]
* [[saitou kaede (yama no susume)|Saitou Kaede]]
* [[Aoba Kokona]]
* [[Kurosaki Honoka]]
* [[Senjuin Koharu]]

title: unicorn_gundam_phenex
body:
A fictional manned giant robot from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse.

[b]RX-0 Unicorn Gundam Phenex[/b]

Third sibling unit to the [[Unicorn Gundam]] and [[Unicorn Gundam Banshee]] [[mobile suit]]s, this time designed with the motif of a [[phoenix]], as its name implies. Unlike the white/red combo of the Unicorn and the black or midnight blue/yellow or orange colors of the Banshee, the Phenex is entirely golden while in Unicorn Mode, gaining blue slots when transformed into [[NT-D|Destroy Mode]]. It possesses wings that double as its shields and funnels in Destroy Mode.

In its animated debut in [[Gundam Narrative]] (2018), tail-like stabilizers are added to its shields.

It is piloted by [[Rita Bernal]] and [spoiler][[Jona Basta]][/spoiler].
other_names: ユニコーンガンダム3号機フェネクス
ユニコーンガンダム3号機

title: unicorn_gundam_banshee
body:
A fictional manned giant robot from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse. It first appeared in the [[Gundam Unicorn]] OVA (2010).

[b]RX-0 Unicorn Gundam Banshee[/b]

Counterpart to the [[Unicorn Gundam]] [[mobile suit]], designed with the motif of a lion instead of a unicorn. Built to the same specifications of the Unicorn Gundam, save the difference in color palette and v-fin ornamentation in [[NT-D]] mode. The Banshee is superior to the Unicorn Gundam in atmospheric combat, but lacks the La+ program plot device.

In the novel, it has been equipped with a Beam Magnum and the shield similar to the Unicorn's. However, in the OVA, it has been given an Armed Armor BS and Armed Armor VN instead of the former armaments. [spoiler] Later on, it is upgraded into Unicorn Banshee Gundam Gundam Banshee Norn, which are equipped with Armed Armor DE and Armed Armor XC, replacing the Armed Armors BS and VN. The Banshee Norn's Beam Magnum has a new attachment called the Revolving Launcher. [/spoiler]

[spoiler]Piloted by [[Marida Cruz]] and later [[Riddhe Marcenas]] (In the OVA however, Marida piloted the regular Banshee while Riddhe piloted the Banshee Norn).[/spoiler]

h4. Other variants
* [[Unicorn Gundam Phenex]]

She has [[long hair|long]] [[brown hair]] with a [[two side up]], [[medium breasts]], and [[brown eyes]]. She wears a [[frilled dress|frilled]] [[red dress|red]] [[layered dress|layered]] & [[pleated dress]], [[fingerless gloves|fingerless]] [[white gloves|white]] [[elbow gloves]], [[red ribbon|red]] [[hair ribbon]]s, [[vambraces]], [[two-tone footwear|two-tone]] [[red footwear|red]] & [[white footwear|white]] [[boots]], [[boobplate]], and a [[brown belt]].

[spoiler]Her name in the real world before the events of Re:Dive was [[Nozomi (real) (princess connect!)|Sakurai Nozomi]].[/spoiler]

title: fortified_suit
body:
A type of [[mecha pilot suit]] from the [[Muv-Luv]] series.

While there are slight variations between the different nations' suits, the general design remains the same - a [[skin tight]] [[bodysuit]] with a [[see-through clothes|see-through]] section on the torso that allows for a full range of movement and deflection of physical attacks, with some metal [[armor]] on the upper arms and lower legs, and an interface system around the head to allow for direct retinal projection of the control displays. 

The male variants of the suit notably have less of the translucent material than the female variants, which have that segment extend down to the inner thighs.

The suit's chin guard is notably absent in [[muv-luv alternative (anime)|Alternative's anime adaptation]].

h4. Examples
* !post #432717: UN design as seen in [[Muv-Luv Alternative|Alternative]]
* !post #5776585: UN redesigns from the [[Muv-Luv Alternative (anime)|Alternative anime]]
* !post #2042190: Japanese Type-00 and Soviet designs as seen in [[Muv-Luv Total Eclipse|Total Eclipse]]
* !post #2245737: East German design as seen in [[Schwarzesmarken]]

title: nileseyy_niles_disappears_(meme)
body:
[b]Nileseyy Niles Disappears[/b] is a photo series based on a "Vine":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vine_(service)] video by the comedian Nileseyy Niles (real name: Niles Stewart).

The photo series is often used on "Black Twitter":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_Twitter] to indicate someone leaving an embarrassing situation.

title: endou_yuuji
body: The loan shark who coerces [[Itou Kaiji]] into going into more debt. Despite his moderately high position in the Teiai Group, he himself is also in a mountain of debt to the higher-ups.

title: kischur_zelretch_schweinorg
body:
One of the five True Magicians, the "Magician of the Second Magic" and also one of the founders of the Clock Tower, holding the title of Wizard Marshal in the Mage's Association. Zelretch is mentioned and briefly appears in many of [[Type-Moon]] works, notably [[Tsukihime]] and [[Fate_(series)|Fate series]], but his origins and details as to how he reached the Second Magic are unknown.

He's the creator of the Mystic Codes [[Magical Ruby]], [[Magical Sapphire]], [[zelretch sword|Jeweled Sword Zelretch]], and [[Keitai-san]].
In [[Fate/Grand Order]] he appears as the illustration cover for the Kaleidoscope [[craft essence_(fate)|]]. Given its popularity, he's also known as "Kaleidoscope" or "the Kaleidoscope guy".
other_names: キシュア・ゼルレッチ・シュバインオーグ

title: gaw
body:
A fictional [[military]] [[aircraft]] from the [[Gundam]] [[mecha]]verse. It first appeared in the [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] anime TV series from 1979.

It is a massive [[mobile suit]] carrier air vehicle operated by the Principality of [[Zeon]].

title: euryale_(fate)
body:
Euryale (Greek for "Far-Flier") is a character from [[Fate/hollow ataraxia]], and can be summoned as an Archer-class Servant in [[Fate/Grand Order]]. Her Noble Phantasm is "Eye of the Euryale", a powerful single-target attack that does more damage and charms the target if it is male.

Has an older twin sister, [[Stheno (fate)|]], and a younger sister, [[Medusa (rider) (fate)|Medusa]]. Depicted as a [[purple hair]]ed girl with [[purple eyes]], [[twintails]], a [[headdress]] and [[white dress]]. The difference between her twin sister is the black rose ornament, the slit, and arm decoration is on her right side. They appear identical in Fate/hollow ataraxia.

Designed by [[Takeuchi Takashi]], [[Akira (kaned fools)]] (Fate/Grand Order) and voiced by [[Asakawa Yuu]].

title: roy_focker
body:
One of the main characters of the [[Choujikuu Yousai Macross]] TV series, the [[Macross: Do You Remember Love?]] movie adaptation, the [[Macross Flashback 2012]] OVA and the [[Macross Zero]] OVA. 

A talented and strong-willed veteran [[mecha]]/fighter ace pilot, he is known for his love of women and alcohol. [b]Roy Focker[/b] is [[Ichijou Hikaru]]'s best friend/sempai and [[Claudia LaSalle]]'s boyfriend. He is also an [[united_states|American]]. 

[spoilers]Roy tragically dies in episode 18 of the original series ("Pineapple Salad") when he bleeds to death after being wounded in battle and refusing to seek medical attention so he could visit his fiance Claudia as she was making a fruit salad for him at the time. As one of the first permanent deaths of a major protagonist animated hero character (shown in the 80s ROBOTECH adaptation in the west), many westerners were very very surprised to see this dark and tragic outcome as it had never EVER happened in cartoons until then.[/spoilers]

His name was spelled [b]Roy Fokker[/b] in [[Robotech]] for two reasons; to correct the reference, and to avoid confusion with a certain word the producers would rather non be said on air.

Roy's mecha of choice are the [[VF-0S]],  the [[VF-1S]] and the [[VF-1 Strike]].

In [[real life]] the design of this anime character was inspired by [[Sleggar Law]] from [[Mobile Suit Gundam]] (1979)[spoiler], who had a similar fate[/spoiler].

title: honest_axe
body:
One of [[Aesop's Fables]] also known as [I]The Honest Woodcutter[/I]. In it, a workman dropped his [[axe]] into the [[river]] (or a [[lake]] or [[pond]] depending on the variations). The god [[Hermes (mythology)|]] found out what was wrong, and offered his aid. First Hermes pulled out a silver axe, and asked whether it was the one the workman lost. He told the god that no, it wasn't. Then Hermes pulled out a golden axe, and asked whether it was his. Again, the workman said no. Finally, Hermes pulled out the original axe, and asked if it was his. The workman said that yes it was his. As a reward for his honesty, Hermes gave him all three axes.

Another workman, hearing of this, purposefully drops his axe into the river. He claims it was the golden axe, and ends up not getting any of them, not even his original axe.

This story appears to have become a common part of Japanese culture, with Mercury replaced by a "water sprite" or some such. It is often parodied, including in an episode of [[Doraemon]] featuring a gadget called the "Woodcutter's Pond" which functions similarly to the fable.

title: monitor_top_refrigerator
body: A [[refrigerator]] design introduced by [[General Electric]] in 1927 and produced into the mid 1930's before being replaced with the more modern "Flat Top" design.  They're an iconic design for their large cylinder or dome-shaped compressor atop the refrigerator.  The initial cylinder shape was reminiscent of the cylinder shaped turret of the [[USS Monitor]] ironclad ship, thus the name "Monitor Top."

title: sash
body:
A large and usually colorful ribbon or band of material worn around the body, usually either:
* Draped diagonally from one shoulder to the opposite hip.
* !post #893699

* Wrapped horizontally around the waist.
* !post #8135112

The [[waist sash]] may be worn as daily attire, but the [[shoulder sash]] is typically worn on ceremonial occasions only. Ceremonial sashes may also be seen in a V-shaped format, draping from both shoulders to the stomach like a large necklace.

An [[obi]] is considered a type of sash that wraps around the waist.
